05203nam a22007815i 9781442688957DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426889577 a10.3138/97814426889572doi  a(DE-B1597)497138  a(OCoLC)1078918935  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0500002bisacsh04a323.61 aIsin, Engin F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecasting the Social in Citizenship /cEngin F. Isin. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tContributors -- t1. Recasting the Social in Citizenship -- t2. The Social in Social Citizenship -- t3. Social Care -- t4. Multicultural Citizenship beyond Recognition -- t5. Between Gender and Cultural Equality -- t6. The Migration-Citizenship Nexus -- t7. The Child-Citizen -- t8. The Soldier-Citizen -- t9. The Securitized Citizen -- t10. The Ecological Citizen -- t11. The City as the Site of the Social -- t12. Conclusion: The Socius of Citizenship -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrevious notions of what constitutes "citizenship" within a country have been steadily challenged by the movement towards a globalized world. Examining the everyday habits of citizens and non-citizens, the contributors to Recasting the Social in Citizenship show how citizenship has increasingly been determined by social behaviours rather than by civil or political affiliations. Broadening the debate by interpreting the social not only as rights and privileges, but also as everyday struggles, this volume offers studies that range from environmental and security issues to transnational migration and military transformations. It further discusses debates over multiculturalism and integration and takes a fresh look at how social activities such as eating, commuting, smoking, as well as sexual habits of citizens and non-citizens have become increasingly governed by the state. Tracing developments in politics and social actions that have bound together citizens and non-citizens, Engin F. Isin and the volume's contributors explore the social sites that have become objects of government, and considers how these subjects are sites of contestation, resistance, differentiation and identification. In doing so, they provide significant insights into the changing states of citizenship and social governance, making Recasting the Social in Citizenship an engaging collection that will be of interest to sociologists, political scientists, and anyone with a concern about immigration and citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspects. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh1 aBilge, Sirma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Janine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Xiaobei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowen, Deborah E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsin, Engin F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsin, Engin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuteau, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKershaw, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLatta, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRygiel, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStasiulis, Daiva, econtributor.4ctb4https://